[2]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 
[3] This speech was about the issue of mass disposal of clothes. In developed countries, including Japan, there is a lot of wasteful spending, such as throwing away clothes after just one visit, or buying the same clothes when you find them. The discarded clothes are sent to developing countries, but the number is now over 15 million each week, which is actually causing a problem. The current mindset of people in developed countries is to use things once and then throw them away. The person giving the speech said that we should change our mindset from a disposable mindset to a mindset of using things with care for a long time.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          
[4]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 
[5] Josephine Philips strongly emphasized the importance of taking great care of your clothes. Her thoughts were influenced by the stories of her grandmother. Her grandmother cherished her favorite dress for more than 60 years and gave it to her grandson, the narrator. This experience guided the narrator when she founded her company, SOJO, providing a fashion-tech solution that's revolutionizing the clothing repair and tailoring industry. Nowadays, few people take good care of their clothes, and many people buy new clothes and easily throw away the old ones. These individual actions have accumulated to create a global problem of overproduction and mass waste of clothing. She says the huge mountain of clothes collected in developing countries show the seriousness of the problem. This issue is not just a problem for governments, laws or corporations, but for us as individuals too. Therefore, she claims to aim for a society where mending and caring for clothes is considered beautiful.

Opinions

five sample opinions

[1] As a generationZ, her presentation was really interesting for me. Honesty, i did not idea about making long term memories with clothes before. So I bought some cheap fast fashion clothes and threw them away frequently. But, recently, I have had many chances to learn about fast fashions and the global environment. So i understand the bad influence of fast fashion and reduce buying that. Then, I noticed one thing. Buying cheap fast fashions makes us spend much more money than buying favorite clothes even if it is more expensive. We can not wear fast fashion items for the long term because of the low quality so throw them away. It is so wasteful. So I changed my mind and bought my favourite clothes.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 
[2] I find Philips' message both powerful and timely. In an era where fast fashion dominates, her call to value and care for our clothing is a crucial reminder of the environmental and personal costs of our consumption habits. The story of her grandmother's dress beautifully illustrates the emotional and historical significance that items of clothing can carry, which is often overlooked in today's disposable culture. Philips' emphasis on repairing and altering clothes instead of discarding them is not only environmentally responsible but also promotes a deeper connection to our belongings. This perspective aligns with the growing movement towards sustainability and conscious consumption. By sharing personal anecdotes, Philips effectively humanizes the issue, making it relatable and inspiring action. Overall, her vision for a culture that values longevity and personal stories in clothing is a compelling alternative to the current trend of fast fashion. It encourages us to rethink our relationship with what we wear, fostering a more sustainable and fulfilling approach to fashion.
[3] > I strongly agree with her idea that buying less can be a climate solution. I am very proud of myself because I rarely buy new products; in addition, I often invent new matches among items I already have so that I will not be bored without buying new ones. I understand that valuing the items and caring for them correctly is important, and I want to suggest to people that they care about what they eat as well as how they look in fashionable outfits. I think people these days are underestimating the importance of what they eat, ending up pursuing brand collections. If they care about organic foods, for example, then they wont have much money to spend on buying new clothing, which has a good impact on both their health and the environment.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      
[4] Listening to this speech, I thought back on my past actions. I am a person who takes better care of things than the average person, and even now I sometimes wear clothes I bought when I was in junior high school or elementary school. If it is a favorite piece of clothing, I think about whether I can repair it before throwing it away. However, I have never thought about the manufacturing process when throwing something away, as the speaker mentioned. I also felt that the same thing can be said about mass production and mass waste industries such as food. Typical examples are when something is a little misshapen and cannot be sold on the market, or has been eaten a little by insects, so it has to be discarded, and so a lot of food is discarded. Farmers try to sell it somehow, making it into juice, jam, or processing it to sell. In today's world, where food shortages are lamented, I thought that if we could reduce this kind of waste, this problem would also be solved.
